{{Refimprove|date=March 2016}}
An '''itinerant poet''' or '''strolling minstrel''' (also known variously as a '''gleeman''', '''circler''', or '''cantabank''') was a wandering [[minstrel]], [[bard]], or other [[poet]] common in [[Middle Ages|medieval]] [[Europe]] but extinct today. From a lower class than [[jester]]s or [[jongleur]]s because he did not have steady work, he instead roamed about to make his living.<ref name=BahnBahn1970>{{Cite book |title = A History of Oral Interpretation |last = Bahn |first = Eugene |chapter= Medieval Period |publisher = Burgess Publishing Co. |year = 1970 |isbn = |location = Minneapolis |pages = 56–57 |first2 = Margaret |last2 = Bahn}}</ref>
== Gleeman == In [[Medieval England]], a gleeman was a reciter of poetry. Like the [[scop]], the gleeman performed poetry to the accompaniment of the harp or "glee wood".<ref name=BahnBahn1970 /> The gleeman occasionally attached himself to a single/particular court but was most often a ''wandering'' entertainer, unlike the scop, who was more static. A gleeman was also less likely to compose or perform his own poetry and relied on the work of others for his material.<ref name=BahnBahn1970 />
