{{member|name=[[Lapu-Lapu]]|nota=Malay tribal chieftain on what is today [[Mactan]] Island, Philippines. Attacked by Spanish and Portuguese under [[Ferdinand Magellan|Fernão de Magalhães]], he fought a defensive battle which resulted in Magalhães's death. Today regarded as the first "Filipino" hero.|ref=}}
{{member|name=Dominador de la Junta Liwanag|nota=Born circa 1950, Dominadór Liwanag, a.k.a. "Tata Casóy," is now a tribal elder of the [[Ambala language|Ambala]] tribe of the [[Aeta people|Aeta]] nation in [[Zambales]] province. He was instructor to the U.S. Marines at the Jungle Environment Survival Training in the rain forest inside the [[U.S. Naval Base Subic Bay|Subic Bay Naval Base]]. He is now the most senior among [[Aeta people|Aetas]] who conduct forest living demonstrations for visitors at Pamulaklakin Forest Trail, [[Subic Bay Freeport Zone|Subic Freeport]], and still wears the traditional Aeta [[Bahag (garment)|bahág]] or loin cloth. He was filmed for the 25th season of the U.S. television series [[Survivor (U.S. TV series)|Survivor]], shot in [[Caramoan, Camarines Sur]].|ref=<ref>He was photographed with another Aeta by the [[Defense Audiovisual Agency]], and the b&w photo (with Liwanag on the left side of the photo) was published in Craighead, Craighead, Smith, Jarvis, 1984, ''How to Survive on Land and Sea'', 4th ed, Annapolis: [[United States Naval Institute|Naval Institute Press]], {{ISBN|0-87021-278-8}}, p 178.</ref>}}
{{member|name=Lawrence Dy Ong|nota=[[Chinese Filipino]] humanitarian. Pupil of Rino Taini, EdD.<ref>A California educator and the proprietor of Pro-Action Associates who, with Mike Conway (LAPD), Randi DuBois (former mayor, [[Colma, California]]) and Cortland Stark (colonel, US Army), took the [[ropes course]] and adventure-based counseling to the Philippines in 1989</ref> As the Activity-Based Counselor of the [[International Catholic Migration Commission]] ESL/CO, he ran the first full-range fully operational [[ropes course]] / [[Adventure therapy|adventure-based counseling]] / team-building course in the Philippines, 1990-1993. Conducted the first formal ropes course / ABC facilitator’s training by a Filipino, 1992.<ref>attended by Gil Acuña, Olaf Bautista, Belle Berania, Gerard Cabrera, Fred Meneses, Benny Osorio, Cindy Ponce, Joseph Sabio, Samuel Salter, Ramona Santos, Dick Semilla, and Edwin Tiu.</ref> Founded<ref>with Samuel Salter</ref> a [[Boy Scouts of America]] troop. Founded<ref>with Cynthia Cruz, Eric Go, Benjamin Navarro, Jose Gerardo Sabio, and Samuel Salter</ref> Kanawan Elementary School<ref>now a government public school</ref> for [[Aeta peoples|Aeta]] children at sitio Kanawan,<ref>an Aeta forest village</ref> Sabang, [[Morong, Bataan]]. Conducted adventure-based counseling with impoverished Filipino [[Amerasian]] youth at [[Subic Bay Freeport Zone]]. Trained the founders of Adventure-Based Counseling Inc.|ref=<ref>Kaisa Research Division, ed, 2001, ''Bridge Builder in Our Midst'', Manila: Kaisa Para Sa Kaunlaran, 2001, {{ISBN|971-8857-23-0}}.</ref> <ref>Suryadinata, Leo, ed, ''Southeast Asian Personalities of Chinese Descent: A Biographical Dictionary'', Singapore: Institute of Southeast Asian Studies, 2012.</ref>}}
