==Other media==

===''Buzz Lightyear of Star Command''===
{{Main|Buzz Lightyear of Star Command}}
'''''Buzz Lightyear of Star Command''''' is a spin-off TV series. The series takes place in the far future. It features Buzz Lightyear (voiced by [[Patrick Warburton]]), a famous, experienced Space Ranger who takes a crew of rookies under his wing as he investigates criminal activity across the galaxy and attempts to bring down Evil Emperor Zurg once and for all. It aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] from October 2, 2000 to January 13, 2001.

===''Buzz Lightyear of Star Command: The Adventure Begins'' (2000)===
{{Main|Buzz Lightyear of Star Command: The Adventure Begins}}
'''''Buzz Lightyear of Star Command: The Adventure Begins''''' is a spin-off animated direct-to-video film, partially based on ''Toy Story''. The film was released on August 8, 2000. It acts as a [[Television Pilot|pilot]] to the television series ''[[Buzz Lightyear of Star Command]]'' and features [[Tim Allen]] as the voice of Buzz Lightyear, who is voiced by [[Patrick Warburton]] in the main series.<ref name="AdBegins2000">{{cite news|last=Stack|first=Peter|title=Buzz Lightyear Tops Stack of Kid Stuff / New Tweety adventure, `Princess Mononoke' also set for release|url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Buzz-Lightyear-Tops-Stack-of-Kid-Stuff-New-2744237.php|access-date=August 31, 2012|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=August 13, 2000}}</ref> In this film, Buzz Lightyear is a space ranger who fights against the evil Emperor Zurg, showing the inspiration for the Buzz Lightyear toyline that exists in the ''Toy Story'' series. Although the film was criticized for not using the same animation as in ''Toy Story'' and ''Toy Story 2'',<ref name="BLEWD">{{cite news|last=Fretts|first=Bruce|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,64853,00.html|title=Buzz Lightyear of Star Command (2008)|date=August 8, 2000|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=March 12, 2009}}</ref> it sold three million VHS and DVDs in its first week of release.<ref name="BL3mil">{{cite news|last=Netherby |first=Jennifer |url=http://www.videobusiness.com/article/CA6302645.html |title=As biggest animated movies stay in Mouse House |date=January 27, 2006 |publisher=VideoBusiness.com |access-date=March 12, 2009 |archivedate=February 11, 2006 |deadurl=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060211203204/http://www.videobusiness.com/article/CA6302645.html }}</ref>

===Comic books===
* A 4-issue limited series, ''Toy Story: Mysterious Stranger'' was published by [[Boom! Studios|Boom! Entertainment]] from May to August 2009. This was followed by an 8-issue ongoing series, starting with #0 in November 2009. Two Buzz Lightyear one-shots were released in 2010, for Free Comic Book Day and Halloween. A second 4-issue limited series, ''Toy Story: Toy Overboard'' was published by Boom! Entertainment from July to October 2010.
* A 4-issue limited series by [[Marvel Comics]] ''Toy Story: Tales from the Toy Chest'' was published from May to August 2012.
*  ''Toy Story magazine'' was first released on 21 July 2010. Each edition was 24 pages in length, apart from the launch edition, which was 28 pages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inpublishing.co.uk/news/articles/egmont_launches_toy_story_magazine.aspx|title=News: Egmont launches Toy Story magazine|author=InPublishing|publisher=inpublishing.co.uk}}</ref>

